abstract:
Understanding the inductive bias and generalization properties of large overparametrized machine learning models requires to characterize the dynamics of the training algorithm.  We study the learning dynamics of large two-layer neural networks via dynamical mean field theory, a well established technique of non-equilibrium statistical physics. We show that, for large network width $m$,
and large number of samples per input dimension $n/d$, the training dynamics exhibits a separation of timescales which implies:
$(i)$ The emergence of a slow time scale associated with the growth in Gaussian/Rademacher complexity of the network;
$(ii)$ Inductive bias towards small complexity if the initialization has small enough complexity;
$(iii)$ A dynamical decoupling between feature learning and overfitting regimes; $(iv)$ A non-monotone behavior of the test error, associated  `feature unlearning' regime at large times.
